er poll =0A<https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2021-11-08/elon-musk=
-did-some-tweets=3Fcmpid=3DBBD110524_MONEYSTUFF&utm_medium=3Demail&utm_sour=
ce=3Dnewsletter&utm_term=3D241105&utm_campaign=3Dmoneystuff>=0A about tax p=
olicy to create a nice distraction.=0A=0AI don=E2=80=99t love this theory o=
r anything, but I understand it. It is a theory of =0Athe form =E2=80=9CElo=
n Musk seems to do a lot of weird stuff, but here is a rational =0Aoverlay =
on his weird stuff that would make it make sense.=E2=80=9D I understand the=
 =0Aurge to make things make sense. But not everything has to make sense.=
=0A=0AAnyway at the Wall Street Journal Spencer Jakab writes =0A<https://ww=
w.wsj.com/business/all-the-presidents-rich-men-79e45218> about =0Asection 1=
043 of the US tax code =0A<https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/1043>=
, which allows employees of =0Athe executive branch of the US government to=
 defer capital gains on property =0Athat they sell to meet conflict-of-inte=
rest requirements when they join the =0Agovernment. Jakab:=0A=0AElon Musk .=
.. has been a major financial backer of Republican presidential =0Acandida=
te Donald Trump and has been floated as a government =E2=80=9Cefficiency cz=
ar.=E2=80=9D =0AHe wrote on his social-media network, X, that =E2=80=9CI lo=
ok forward to serving =0AAmerica if the opportunity arises. No pay, no titl=
e, no recognition is needed.=E2=80=9D=0A=0AA 34-year-old law might make a t=
ransition pretty lucrative, though. With most =0Aof Musk=E2=80=99s estimate=
d $200 billion-plus fortune in shares of companies such as =0ATesla and Spa=
ceX, and Musk still fighting for a controversial $46 billion =0Aoption awar=
d from Tesla, he could sell those stakes and defer capital-gains =0Ataxes=
=E2=80=94potentially forever=E2=80=94by putting them into government securi=
ties or =0Adiversified mutual funds.=0A=0AAgain I do not actually believe a=
 theory like =E2=80=9CElon Musk has decided to back =0ADonald Trump and vol=
unteer to serve in his administration in order to sell his =0ATesla stake a=
nd invest the proceeds in a diversified portfolio without paying =0Ataxes o=
r sending negative signals about the value of Tesla.=E2=80=9D For one thing=
, I =0Aam not convinced that actually doing that would be a good financial =
trade for =0Ahim, or that he wouldwant to diversify out of his portfolio of=
 Mars-ish =0Acompanies =0A<https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2024-=
10-17/musk-keeps-paying-for-x=3Fcmpid=3DBBD110524_MONEYSTUFF&utm_medium=3De=
mail&utm_source=3Dnewsletter&utm_term=3D241105&utm_campaign=3Dmoneystuff>=
=0A. For another, I doubt anyone in a Trump administration would care about=
 =0Aconflicts of interest, and Musk would clearly just keep his Tesla and S=
paceX =0Astakes while also overseeing government efficiency. Still it is a =
fun theory, =0Areducing Musk=E2=80=99s recent political turn to a way to sa=
ve on capital gains taxes.=0A=0AElsewhere here is some speculation =0A<http=
